00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:23.850
Or another idea… and this one is my personal
favorite.

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:27.920
Researchers from Lund University, in Sweden
think acetaminophen actually works on the

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:28.920
endocannabinoid system.

00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:33.490
If that word sounds a little familiar to you,
yes, it’s the system that respond to cannabis

00:02:33.490 --> 00:02:34.490
or weed.

00:02:34.490 --> 00:02:37.400
But it’s also involved in a lot of different
processes like appetite, pain-sensation, mood,

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:38.400
and memory.

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:41.990
So the researchers claim that acetaminophen
activates two ion channels in the brain and

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:45.540
spinal cord and that these channels also respond
to certain cannabinoids.

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:50.290
But the researchers caution that these channels
can actually trigger pain and itch responses,

00:02:50.290 --> 00:02:52.819
so it seems odd that activating them reduces
pain.

00:02:52.819 --> 00:02:54.480
But they might be on to something.

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:58.290
Another study published in the European Journal
of Pharmacology shows that that blocking cannabinoid

00:02:58.290 --> 00:03:01.900
receptor type 1 prevents acetaminophen from
relieving pain in mice.

00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:05.740
And there’s a few other ideas of how the
drug works, like maybe it works on serotonin

00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:07.520
receptors, but who really knows right now.

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:11.950
So even for a drug as old as acetaminophen…
it’s clear more research is needed.

00:03:11.950 --> 00:03:15.910
Alright guys, the question is, are you a fan
of ibuprofen or acetaminophen?

00:03:15.910 --> 00:03:17.710
Does one work better for you than the other?

00:03:17.710 --> 00:03:18.430
Let us know..

